# .NET Framework → .NET 8 Migration: BackgroundProcessor

## Critical Breaking Changes

1. **`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** in .NET 5+. It's completely removed.
2. **`ThreadAbortException` will never be thrown** — catching it is dead code.
3. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` also throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`**.

The modern replacement is **`CancellationToken`** with cooperative cancellation.

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Task? _workerTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass token so blocking calls become cancellable
                var item = await GetNextItemAsync(token);
                await ProcessItemAsync(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Graceful shutdown requested — roll back partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit the loop cleanly
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public async Task StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerTask is null)
            return;

        timeout ??= TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5);

        // Signal cancellation (cooperative — no forced abort)
        _cts.Cancel();

        // Wait for the worker to finish, with a timeout
        if (await Task.WhenAny(_workerTask, Task.Delay(timeout.Value)) != _workerTask)
        {
            // Worker didn't stop in time — log a warning.
            // In .NET 8 there is NO way to forcibly kill it.
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _cts?.Cancel();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Blocking `GetNextItem()` ignores cancellation** | If the old method blocks on a `Queue.Dequeue` or DB call, cancellation can't interrupt it. You **must** pass `CancellationToken` into blocking APIs (e.g., `Channel.ReadAsync(token)`, `SemaphoreSlim.WaitAsync(token)`). |
| **No forced termination exists** | .NET 8 has no `Thread.Abort` equivalent. If code truly hangs, you cannot kill it in-process. Design all I/O to accept cancellation tokens. |
| **`Thread.Sleep` → `Task.Delay`** | `Thread.Sleep` blocks a thread pool thread. Use `await Task.Delay(ms, token)` instead. |
| **Fire-and-forget `Task.Run`** | Unobserved exceptions silently vanish. Store the `Task` and `await` it in `StopAsync` to surface errors. |
| **`volatile bool` is insufficient** | It worked for `Thread.Abort` patterns, but `CancellationToken` is the idiomatic and more capable replacement — it can wake up blocked `WaitAsync`/`ReadAsync` calls. A `volatile bool` cannot. |
| **`IDisposable`** | `CancellationTokenSource` is disposable. The class should implement `IDisposable` to avoid leaks. |

## If You Can't Make Everything Async

For sync-only code that truly cannot be refactored:

```csharp
private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
{
    while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        try
        {
            // Poll the token instead of blocking forever
            var item = GetNextItem(token); // must check token internally
            ProcessItem(item);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            RollbackCurrentTransaction();
            break;
        }
        finally
        {
            FlushBuffers();
        }
    }
}
```

The key design shift: .NET 8 requires **cooperative** cancellation. Every blocking call must accept and honor a `CancellationToken` — there is no escape hatch.
